{"title_page": "Secret Treaty of Dover", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2013}}\n[[File:King Charles II (Lely).jpg|right|thumb|150px|Charles II]]\n\nThe '''Treaty of Dover''', also known as the '''Secret Treaty of Dover''', was a treaty between England and France signed at [[Dover]] on 1 June<ref>''Madame, a Life of Henrietta, Daughter of Charles I and Duchess of Orleans'' by J. Cartwright, Seeley and Co. Ltd., London, 1894, p. 332 [https://books.google.com/books?id=KlBBAAAAIAAJ]</ref> 1670.  It required that [[Charles II of England]] would convert to the [[Roman Catholic Church]] and assist [[Louis XIV]] with 60 warships to help and 4000 soldiers in France's war of conquest against the [[Dutch Republic]]. In exchange, Charles would secretly receive a yearly pension of \u00a3230,000, as well as an extra sum of money when Charles informed the English people of his conversion, and France would send 6,000 French troops if there was ever a rebellion against Charles in England.   The secret treaty was signed by Arlington, Arundell, Clifford and Bellings for England and Colbert de Croissy for France.  Both kings exchanged letters of ratification and kept secret the existence of the treaty.<ref>G.M.D. Howat, ''Stuart and Cromwellian Foreign Policy'' (1974) pp 126\u201332.</ref>  A public treaty of Dover was also negotiated, but it was a fake designed for propaganda and to hide the religious dimension of the secret treaty. The [[Third Anglo-Dutch War]] was a direct consequence of this treaty.<ref>Ronald Hutton, \"The Making of the Secret Treaty of Dover, 1668\u20131670.\" pp. 302-303.</ref> The actual treaty was published by historians a century later.\n\n==Negotiation and provisions==\n[[File:Mignard, possibly after - Henrietta of England - National Portrait Gallery.jpg|right|thumb|150px|Henrietta, Charles II's youngest sister, assisted in the negotiations that led to the Secret Treaty of Dover (26 May 1670).<ref>{{citation | first = Stephen | last = Coote | title = Royal Survivor: The Life of Charles II | year = 2000 | ISBN = 0-312-22687-X | url-access = registration | url = https://archive.org/details/royalsurvivorlif00coot }}.</ref>]]\nExactly who first proposed the alliance between the two kingdoms is unknown, as is the date when the possibility was first discussed. Although the two nations had secretly discussed forming a closer relationship after [[The Restoration]], and Charles suggested an Anglo-French treaty.<ref>Gijs Rommelse, ''The Second Anglo-Dutch War (1665-1667)'', pp 29-30.</ref> Charles' assumption that Louis would prefer such a treaty to one with the Dutch was mistaken, as an English treaty was not necessary for Louis' objectives in the [[Spanish Netherlands]], but one with the Dutch Republic was,<ref>Gijs Rommelse, ''The Second Anglo-Dutch War (1665-1667)'' (2004) pp 65,109.</ref> After the signature of a Franco-Dutch defensive treaty in 1662, relations between England and France continued to deteriorate until a French declaration of war against England in January 1666.<ref>Gijs Rommelse, ''The Second Anglo-Dutch War (1665-1667)'', p 151.</ref>    \n \nDuring the [[Second Anglo-Dutch War]], mutual suspicion grew between the Dutch and Louis, and following its end and the start of the [[War of Devolution]], both in 1667, a [[Triple Alliance (1668)]] was former between the Dutch Republic, England and Sweden was formed in 1668 to counter French aggression in the Spanish Netherlands.<ref>Ronald Hutton, \"The Making of the Secret Treaty of Dover, 1668\u20131670.\" pp 299-300.</ref> During 1669, friction between the members of the Triple Alliance convinced Louis that he could detach either England or the Dutch Republic from it and, following an unsuccessful attempt to negotiate with the Dutch, he was approached by Charles, who used his sister as point of contact, to form an alliance.<ref>Ronald Hutton, \"The Making of the Secret Treaty of Dover, 1668\u20131670.\" pp 300-301.</ref> The only participants in the talks to begin with were [[Louis XIV of France|Louis XIV]] of France, [[Charles II of England|Charles II]] of England, and Charles's sister [[Princess Henrietta of England|Henrietta]], ''[[duchesse d'Orl\u00e9ans]]''. Louis was first cousin to Charles (through their grandfather [[Henry IV of France]]).  Henrietta was also Louis's sister-in-law through her marriage to his only brother [[Philippe I, Duke of Orl\u00e9ans|Phillippe, ''duc d'Orl\u00e9ans'']].<ref>David Ogg, ''England in the Reign of Charles II'' (2nd ed. 1936) vol 1 p 342-44.</ref>\n\nCharles' motives for entering into secret negotiations with France while England was part of the Triple Alliance opposed to France have been the subject of considerable discussion. His suggested motives include a desire to to have Europe's strongest state as an ally, to make himself politically and financially independent of parliament, to ensure that England received a share of the [[Spanish Empire]] if and when it broke up, to use Catholics, and possibly also Protestant dissenters, as a dependable group of supporters to strengthen his monarchy or to revenge himself on the Dutch and particularly its republican government. However, as Charles initially attempted to form an alliance with France without abandoning the Triple Alliance, he was not as consistent in opposing the Dutch republican government as Louis was.<ref>Ronald Hutton, \"The Making of the Secret Treaty of Dover, 1668\u20131670.\" pp. 297, 300-301.</ref> Since the provisions of the 1659 [[Treaty of the Pyrenees]] included the marriage of Louis to [[Maria Theresa of Spain|Maria Theresa]], eldest daughter of [[Philip IV of Spain]], and despite Maria Theresa renouncing her inheritance rights, Louis consistently manoeuvred to acquire Spanish territory adjacent to France and to promote his wife's claim to the Spanish throne.<ref>Gijs Rommelse, ''The Second Anglo-Dutch War (1665-1667)'', pp 28, 34.</ref>  \n \nBy the secret treaty Charles was to abandon the Triple Alliance with Sweden and the [[Dutch Republic]] in favour of assisting Louis in conquering the Dutch Republic.  Provided that the conquest was successfully completed, England was promised several very profitable ports along one of the major rivers that run through the Dutch Republic.<ref>Ogg, ''England in the Reign of Charles II'' vol 1 pp 344-46.</ref>  The main components of the treaty can be paraphrased:\n\n{{quote |The King of England will make a public profession of the Catholic faith, and will receive the sum of two millions of crowns, to aid him in this project, from the Most Christian King, in the course of the next six months.  The date of this declaration is left absolutely to his own pleasure.  The King of France will faithfully observe the [[Treaty of Aix-la-Chapelle (1668)|Treaty of Aix-la-Chapelle]], as regards Spain, and the King of England will maintain the Treaty of the [[Triple Alliance (1668)|Triple Alliance]] in a similar manner.  If new rights to the Spanish monarchy revert to the King of France, the King of England will aid him in maintaining these rights.  The two Kings will declare war against the United Provinces.  The King of France will attack them by land, and will receive the help of 6000 men from England.  The King of England will send 50 men-of-war to sea, and the King of France 30; the combined fleets will be under the [[James II of England|Duke of York]]'s command.  His Britannic Majesty will be content to receive [[Walcheren]], the mouth of the [[Scheldt]], and the isle of [[Cadzand]], as his share of the conquered provinces.  Separate articles will provide for the interests of the [[William III of England|Prince of Orange]].  The Treaty of Commerce, which has already begun, shall be concluded as promptly as possible.<ref>Andrew Browning, ed. ''English Historical Documents: 1660-1714'' (Eyre & Spottiswoode, 1953), pp 863-67 for text; paraphrase by [[Fran\u00e7ois Mignet]] from Julia Ady, ''Madame'' (1894) pp. 332\u201333.</ref>}}\n\nThe secret treaty did not in fact become public until 1771 after the historian Sir [[Sir John Dalrymple, 4th Baronet|John Dalrymple]] published its contents in his ''Memoirs of Great Britain and Ireland''.<ref>J. P. Kenyon, ''The History Men. The Historical Profession in England since the Renaissance. Second Edition'' (Weidenfeld and Nicolson, 1993), pp. 67-68.</ref> Had it been published in Charles II's lifetime, the results might have been drastic; considering the enormous effect of [[Titus Oates]]' highly unreliable assertions of a [[Popish Plot]], an even greater backlash might have followed had the English public learned that the King actually obliged himself to turn Catholic and that he was willing to rely on French troops to impose that conversion on his own subjects.\n\n==The \"cover\" treaty==\nThe [[secret treaty]] was signed and sealed in June 1670.  The [[George Villiers, 2nd Duke of Buckingham|Duke of Buckingham]] was then appointed to negotiate a treaty with the King of France.  He was amazed by how smoothly it went.  This treaty closely followed the secret treaty just concluded, but the clause by which King Charles was to declare himself a Roman Catholic as soon as the affairs of his kingdom permitted did not appear; neither, therefore, did the stipulation that the attack on the Netherlands would follow his declaration.  This treaty was signed by all five members of the [[Cabal Ministry]] on 21 December 1670 and was made known to the public. However King Charles and the French knew it was a meaningless fake.<ref>Antonia Fraser, ''Royal Charles: Charles II and the Restoration'' (1979), pp. 275&ndash;276</ref><ref>Ogg, ''England in the Reign of Charles II'' vol 1 pp 346-48.</ref><ref>Tim Harris, ''Restoration: Charles II and his kingdoms, 1660-1685'' (2006) p 71.</ref>\n\n==Consequences==\n{{more citations needed|section|date=May 2018}}<!--2 paragraphs without citations-->\nMilitary preparations took some time.  Louis declared war on the Dutch on 6 April 1672, and Charles followed suit the next day.  The [[Third Anglo-Dutch War]] failed to go off as originally planned.  The costs of deploying the English fleet were much greater than expected, and the money sent by Louis to offset the costs did not come close to enough.  Furthermore, the Dutch, led by [[William III of England|Captain-General William of Orange]] put up a much better fight than expected. Desperate for funds, Charles was forced to call Parliament into session for the first time in over two years. He had hoped to keep it [[legislative session#Procedure in Commonwealth realms|prorogued]] in order to wage the war without its oversight.  In 1674, largely because of pressure put upon Charles by Parliament, England signed the [[Treaty of Westminster (1674)|Treaty of Westminster]] ending their involvement in the third Anglo-Dutch War.  The French would continue to fight for four more years before signing the [[Treaty of Nijmegen]].\n\nIn 1672, Charles issued a [[Royal Declaration of Indulgence|Declaration of Indulgence]] which suspended the penal laws against [[Nonconformist (Protestantism)|nonconforming]] Protestants and also relaxed (but did not suspend) the penal laws applying to Roman Catholics.  When Parliament reconvened that year, they denounced the Declaration and announced that the English monarch did not possess the power to issue proclamations that suspended penal laws passed by the Parliament. Furthermore, they refused to fund the ongoing [[Third Anglo-Dutch War]] until the declaration was withdrawn. Charles was forced to comply with Parliament's demands, thereby ending the chance offered by the treaty of reconciling England with the Roman Catholic Church.<ref>Ogg, ''England in the Reign of Charles II'' vol 1 pp 354-55, 365-68.</ref>\n\nThe treaty's reference to the possibility of \"new rights to the Spanish monarchy reverting to the King of France\" envisaged the possibility of the Spanish King [[Charles II of Spain|Charles]] dying childless, and of Louis then claiming the Spanish throne for the House of Bourbon. At the time of the treaty, the Spanish monarch was only nine years old, but his infirmity was already evident and well-known, casting doubt on his ever being able to beget children. However, by the time when it did happen - the King of Spain indeed dying childless in 1700 - the orientation of British foreign policy had completely reversed. Far from the King of England aiding the French one in \"maintaining his Spanish rights\", Britain went to a major war - the [[War of Spanish Succession]] - in order to block these French ambitions.\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of treaties]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{citation | last = Ady | first = Julia | title = Madame, a Life of Henrietta, Daughter of Charles I and Duchess of Orleans |  publisher = Seeley & Co | place = London | year = 1894 | pages = 332\u201333 | url = https://archive.org/stream/madamealifehenr02adygoog#page/n354/mode/2up}}.\n* Black, Jeremy. \"British Foreign Policy and International Affairs during Sir William Trumbull's Career.\" ''The British Library Journal'' 19.2 (1993): 199-217.\n* Browning, Andrew, ed. ''English historical documents: 1660-1714'' (Eyre & Spottiswoode, 1953), pp 863\u201367 for text.\n* Bryant, Arthur. ''King Charles II'' (1955), pp.&nbsp;154\u201368.\n* Feiling, Keith. ''British Foreign Policy 1660-1672'' (1930). [https://books.google.com/books?id=o13GLzw8dpkC excerpt 1968 reprint]\n* Howat, G.M.D. ''Stuart and Cromwellian Foreign Policy'' (1974) pp 95\u2013138.\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Hutton | first1 = R | year = 1986 | title = 'The Making of the Secret Treaty of Dover, 1668\u20131670 | url = | journal = The Historical Journal | volume = 29 | issue = 2| pages = 297\u2013318 | doi = 10.1017/S0018246X00018756 }}\n* Jones, J. R. ''Country and Court'' (1978),  pp 64\u201373.\n* Lodge, Richard. \"English Foreign Policy, 1660\u20131715\" ''History'' 15#60 (1931) pp 296\u2013307.\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Maurice | first1 = D. Lee Jr | year = 1961 | title = The Earl of Arlington and the Treaty of Dover | journal = Journal of British Studies | volume = 1 | issue = 1| pages = 58\u201370 | jstor=175099 | doi=10.1086/385435}}\n* Miller, John. ''Popery and politics in England'' (Cambridge UP, 1973), pp.&nbsp;108\u201314.\n* Ogg, David. '' England in the Reign of Charles II'' (2nd ed. 2 vol 1936)\n* Rommelse, Gijs, ''The Second Anglo-Dutch War (1665-1667): Raison D'\u00e9tat, Mercantilism and Maritime Strife'' (Verloren, 2006).\n\n[[Category:1670 in England]]\n[[Category:1670 in France]]\n[[Category:Anglo-Dutch Wars]]\n[[Category:Secret treaties|Dover]]\n[[Category:Treaties of England|Dover]]\n[[Category:History of Dover, Kent]]\n[[Category:Military history of Dover, Kent]]\n[[Category:1670 treaties]]\n[[Category:Treaties of the Kingdom of France|Dover]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2013}}\n[[File:King Charles II (Lely).jpg|right|thumb|150px|Charles II]]\n\nThe '''Treaty of Dover''', also known as the '''Secret Treaty of Dover''', was a treaty between England and France signed at [[Dover]] on 1 June<ref>''Madame, a Life of Henrietta, Daughter of Charles I and Duchess of Orleans'' by J. Cartwright, Seeley and Co. Ltd., London, 1894, p. 332 [https://books.google.com/books?id=KlBBAAAAIAAJ]</ref> 1670.  It required that [[Charles II of England]] would convert to the [[Roman Catholic Church]] and assist [[Louis XIV]] with 60 warships to help and 4000 soldiers in France's war of conquest against the [[Dutch Republic]]. In exchange, Charles would secretly receive a yearly pension of \u00a3230,000, as well as an extra sum of money when Charles informed the English people of his conversion, and France would send 6,000 French troops if there was ever a rebellion against Charles in England.   The secret treaty was signed by Arlington, Arundell, Clifford and Bellings for England and Colbert de Croissy for France.  Both kings exchanged letters of ratification and kept secret the existence of the treaty.<ref>G.M.D. Howat, ''Stuart and Cromwellian Foreign Policy'' (1974) pp 126\u201332.</ref>  A public treaty of Dover was also negotiated, but it was a fake designed for propaganda and to hide the religious dimension of the secret treaty. The [[Third Anglo-Dutch War]] was a direct consequence of this treaty.<ref>Ronald Hutton, \"The Making of the Secret Treaty of Dover, 1668\u20131670.\" pp. 302-303.</ref> The actual treaty was published by historians a century later.\n\n==Negotiation and provisions==\n[[File:Mignard, possibly after - Henrietta of England - National Portrait Gallery.jpg|right|thumb|150px|Henrietta, Charles II's youngest sister, assisted in the negotiations that led to the Secret Treaty of Dover (26 May 1670).<ref>{{citation | first = Stephen | last = Coote | title = Royal Survivor: The Life of Charles II | year = 2000 | ISBN = 0-312-22687-X | url-access = registration | url = https://archive.org/details/royalsurvivorlif00coot }}.</ref>]]\nExactly who first proposed the alliance between the two kingdoms is unknown, as is the date when the possibility was first discussed. Although the two nations had secretly discussed forming a closer relationship after [[The Restoration]], and Charles suggested an Anglo-French treaty.<ref>Gijs Rommelse, ''The Second Anglo-Dutch War (1665-1667)'', pp 29-30.</ref> Charles' assumption that Louis would prefer such a treaty to one with the Dutch was mistaken, as an English treaty was not necessary for Louis' objectives in the [[Spanish Netherlands]], but one with the Dutch Republic was,<ref>Gijs Rommelse, ''The Second Anglo-Dutch War (1665-1667)'' (2004) pp 65,109.</ref> After the signature of a Franco-Dutch defensive treaty in 1662, relations between England and France continued to deteriorate until a French declaration of war against England in January 1666.<ref>Gijs Rommelse, ''The Second Anglo-Dutch War (1665-1667)'', p 151.</ref>    \n \nDuring the [[Second Anglo-Dutch War]], mutual suspicion grew between the Dutch and Louis, and following its end and the start of the [[War of Devolution]], both in 1667, a [[Triple Alliance (1668)]] was former between the Dutch Republic, England and Sweden was formed in 1668 to counter French aggression in the Spanish Netherlands.<ref>Ronald Hutton, \"The Making of the Secret Treaty of Dover, 1668\u20131670.\" pp 299-300.</ref> During 1669, friction between the members of the Triple Alliance convinced Louis that he could detach either England or the Dutch Republic from it and, following an unsuccessful attempt to negotiate with the Dutch, he was approached by Charles, who used his sister as point of contact, to form an alliance.<ref>Ronald Hutton, \"The Making of the Secret Treaty of Dover, 1668\u20131670.\" pp 300-301.</ref> The only participants in the talks to begin with were [[Louis XIV of France|Louis XIV]] of France, [[Charles II of England|Charles II]] of England, and Charles's sister [[Princess Henrietta of England|Henrietta]], ''[[duchesse d'Orl\u00e9ans]]''. Louis was first cousin to Charles (through their grandfather [[Henry IV of France]]).  Henrietta was also Louis's sister-in-law through her marriage to his only brother [[Philippe I, Duke of Orl\u00e9ans|Phillippe, ''duc d'Orl\u00e9ans'']].<ref>David Ogg, ''England in the Reign of Charles II'' (2nd ed. 1936) vol 1 p 342-44.</ref>\n\nCharles' motives for entering into secret negotiations with France while England was part of the Triple Alliance opposed to France have been the subject of considerable discussion. His suggested motives include a desire to to have Europe's strongest state as an ally, to make himself politically and financially independent of parliament, to ensure that England received a share of the [[Spanish Empire]] if and when it broke up, to use Catholics, and possibly also Protestant dissenters, as a dependable group of supporters to strengthen his monarchy or to revenge himself on the Dutch and particularly its republican government. However, as Charles initially attempted to form an alliance with France without abandoning the the Triple Alliance, he was not as consistent in opposing the Dutch republican government as Louis was.<ref>Ronald Hutton, \"The Making of the Secret Treaty of Dover, 1668\u20131670.\" pp. 297, 300-301.</ref> Since the provisions of the 1659 [[Treaty of the Pyrenees]] included the marriage of Louis to [[Maria Theresa of Spain|Maria Theresa]], eldest daughter of [[Philip IV of Spain]], and despite Maria Theresa renouncing her inheritance rights, Louis consistently manoeuvred to acquire Spanish territory adjacent to France and to promote his wife's claim to the Spanish throne.<ref>Gijs Rommelse, ''The Second Anglo-Dutch War (1665-1667)'', pp 28, 34.</ref>  \n \nBy the secret treaty Charles was to abandon the Triple Alliance with Sweden and the [[Dutch Republic]] in favour of assisting Louis in conquering the Dutch Republic.  Provided that the conquest was successfully completed, England was promised several very profitable ports along one of the major rivers that run through the Dutch Republic.<ref>Ogg, ''England in the Reign of Charles II'' vol 1 pp 344-46.</ref>  The main components of the treaty can be paraphrased:\n\n{{quote |The King of England will make a public profession of the Catholic faith, and will receive the sum of two millions of crowns, to aid him in this project, from the Most Christian King, in the course of the next six months.  The date of this declaration is left absolutely to his own pleasure.  The King of France will faithfully observe the [[Treaty of Aix-la-Chapelle (1668)|Treaty of Aix-la-Chapelle]], as regards Spain, and the King of England will maintain the Treaty of the [[Triple Alliance (1668)|Triple Alliance]] in a similar manner.  If new rights to the Spanish monarchy revert to the King of France, the King of England will aid him in maintaining these rights.  The two Kings will declare war against the United Provinces.  The King of France will attack them by land, and will receive the help of 6000 men from England.  The King of England will send 50 men-of-war to sea, and the King of France 30; the combined fleets will be under the [[James II of England|Duke of York]]'s command.  His Britannic Majesty will be content to receive [[Walcheren]], the mouth of the [[Scheldt]], and the isle of [[Cadzand]], as his share of the conquered provinces.  Separate articles will provide for the interests of the [[William III of England|Prince of Orange]].  The Treaty of Commerce, which has already begun, shall be concluded as promptly as possible.<ref>Andrew Browning, ed. ''English Historical Documents: 1660-1714'' (Eyre & Spottiswoode, 1953), pp 863-67 for text; paraphrase by [[Fran\u00e7ois Mignet]] from Julia Ady, ''Madame'' (1894) pp. 332\u201333.</ref>}}\n\nThe secret treaty did not in fact become public until 1771 after the historian Sir [[Sir John Dalrymple, 4th Baronet|John Dalrymple]] published its contents in his ''Memoirs of Great Britain and Ireland''.<ref>J. P. Kenyon, ''The History Men. The Historical Profession in England since the Renaissance. Second Edition'' (Weidenfeld and Nicolson, 1993), pp. 67-68.</ref> Had it been published in Charles II's lifetime, the results might have been drastic; considering the enormous effect of [[Titus Oates]]' highly unreliable assertions of a [[Popish Plot]], an even greater backlash might have followed had the English public learned that the King actually obliged himself to turn Catholic and that he was willing to rely on French troops to impose that conversion on his own subjects.\n\n==The \"cover\" treaty==\nThe [[secret treaty]] was signed and sealed in June 1670.  The [[George Villiers, 2nd Duke of Buckingham|Duke of Buckingham]] was then appointed to negotiate a treaty with the King of France.  He was amazed by how smoothly it went.  This treaty closely followed the secret treaty just concluded, but the clause by which King Charles was to declare himself a Roman Catholic as soon as the affairs of his kingdom permitted did not appear; neither, therefore, did the stipulation that the attack on the Netherlands would follow his declaration.  This treaty was signed by all five members of the [[Cabal Ministry]] on 21 December 1670 and was made known to the public. However King Charles and the French knew it was a meaningless fake.<ref>Antonia Fraser, ''Royal Charles: Charles II and the Restoration'' (1979), pp. 275&ndash;276</ref><ref>Ogg, ''England in the Reign of Charles II'' vol 1 pp 346-48.</ref><ref>Tim Harris, ''Restoration: Charles II and his kingdoms, 1660-1685'' (2006) p 71.</ref>\n\n==Consequences==\n{{more citations needed|section|date=May 2018}}<!--2 paragraphs without citations-->\nMilitary preparations took some time.  Louis declared war on the Dutch on 6 April 1672, and Charles followed suit the next day.  The [[Third Anglo-Dutch War]] failed to go off as originally planned.  The costs of deploying the English fleet were much greater than expected, and the money sent by Louis to offset the costs did not come close to enough.  Furthermore, the Dutch, led by [[William III of England|Captain-General William of Orange]] put up a much better fight than expected. Desperate for funds, Charles was forced to call Parliament into session for the first time in over two years. He had hoped to keep it [[legislative session#Procedure in Commonwealth realms|prorogued]] in order to wage the war without its oversight.  In 1674, largely because of pressure put upon Charles by Parliament, England signed the [[Treaty of Westminster (1674)|Treaty of Westminster]] ending their involvement in the third Anglo-Dutch War.  The French would continue to fight for four more years before signing the [[Treaty of Nijmegen]].\n\nIn 1672, Charles issued a [[Royal Declaration of Indulgence|Declaration of Indulgence]] which suspended the penal laws against [[Nonconformist (Protestantism)|nonconforming]] Protestants and also relaxed (but did not suspend) the penal laws applying to Roman Catholics.  When Parliament reconvened that year, they denounced the Declaration and announced that the English monarch did not possess the power to issue proclamations that suspended penal laws passed by the Parliament. Furthermore, they refused to fund the ongoing [[Third Anglo-Dutch War]] until the declaration was withdrawn. Charles was forced to comply with Parliament's demands, thereby ending the chance offered by the treaty of reconciling England with the Roman Catholic Church.<ref>Ogg, ''England in the Reign of Charles II'' vol 1 pp 354-55, 365-68.</ref>\n\nThe treaty's reference to the possibility of \"new rights to the Spanish monarchy reverting to the King of France\" envisaged the possibility of the Spanish King [[Charles II of Spain|Charles]] dying childless, and of Louis then claiming the Spanish throne for the House of Bourbon. At the time of the treaty, the Spanish monarch was only nine years old, but his infirmity was already evident and well-known, casting doubt on his ever being able to beget children. However, by the time when it did happen - the King of Spain indeed dying childless in 1700 - the orientation of British foreign policy had completely reversed. Far from the King of England aiding the French one in \"maintaining his Spanish rights\", Britain went to a major war - the [[War of Spanish Succession]] - in order to block these French ambitions.\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of treaties]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{citation | last = Ady | first = Julia | title = Madame, a Life of Henrietta, Daughter of Charles I and Duchess of Orleans |  publisher = Seeley & Co | place = London | year = 1894 | pages = 332\u201333 | url = https://archive.org/stream/madamealifehenr02adygoog#page/n354/mode/2up}}.\n* Black, Jeremy. \"British Foreign Policy and International Affairs during Sir William Trumbull's Career.\" ''The British Library Journal'' 19.2 (1993): 199-217.\n* Browning, Andrew, ed. ''English historical documents: 1660-1714'' (Eyre & Spottiswoode, 1953), pp 863\u201367 for text.\n* Bryant, Arthur. ''King Charles II'' (1955), pp.&nbsp;154\u201368.\n* Feiling, Keith. ''British Foreign Policy 1660-1672'' (1930). [https://books.google.com/books?id=o13GLzw8dpkC excerpt 1968 reprint]\n* Howat, G.M.D. ''Stuart and Cromwellian Foreign Policy'' (1974) pp 95\u2013138.\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Hutton | first1 = R | year = 1986 | title = 'The Making of the Secret Treaty of Dover, 1668\u20131670 | url = | journal = The Historical Journal | volume = 29 | issue = 2| pages = 297\u2013318 | doi = 10.1017/S0018246X00018756 }}\n* Jones, J. R. ''Country and Court'' (1978),  pp 64\u201373.\n* Lodge, Richard. \"English Foreign Policy, 1660\u20131715\" ''History'' 15#60 (1931) pp 296\u2013307.\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Maurice | first1 = D. Lee Jr | year = 1961 | title = The Earl of Arlington and the Treaty of Dover | journal = Journal of British Studies | volume = 1 | issue = 1| pages = 58\u201370 | jstor=175099 | doi=10.1086/385435}}\n* Miller, John. ''Popery and politics in England'' (Cambridge UP, 1973), pp.&nbsp;108\u201314.\n* Ogg, David. '' England in the Reign of Charles II'' (2nd ed. 2 vol 1936)\n* Rommelse, Gijs, ''The Second Anglo-Dutch War (1665-1667): Raison D'\u00e9tat, Mercantilism and Maritime Strife'' (Verloren, 2006).\n\n[[Category:1670 in England]]\n[[Category:1670 in France]]\n[[Category:Anglo-Dutch Wars]]\n[[Category:Secret treaties|Dover]]\n[[Category:Treaties of England|Dover]]\n[[Category:History of Dover, Kent]]\n[[Category:Military history of Dover, Kent]]\n[[Category:1670 treaties]]\n[[Category:Treaties of the Kingdom of France|Dover]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Duplicate word removed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Secret_Treaty_of_Dover"}
{"title_page": "Chanell stone", "text_new": "{{Infobox artist\n| name             = Chanell Stone\n| birth_date       = [[1992]]\n| birth_place      = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], [[United States]]\n| nationality      = American\n| field            = [[Photography]]\n| alma_mater       = [[California College of the Arts]]\n                   and [[Los Angeles Trade-Technical College]]\n| awards           = 2020 Artist in Residence, Real Time and Space\n2019-2020 Emerging Artist Award, [[Museum of the African Diaspora]], San Francisco\n2018-2019  Purchase Prize Award, [[Center for Photography at Woodstock]]\n| website          = {{URL|https://www.chanellstone.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Chanell Stone''' is an African American [[photographer]] living and working in [[Oakland, California]].\n\n== Early life and education ==\nStone\u00a0 received a [[Bachelor of Fine Arts|B.F.A.]] in [[photography]] from [[California College of the Arts]] in 2019. She received an [[associate degree]] in [[English]] from [[Los Angeles Trade-Technical College]] in 2017. \n\n== Work ==\nChanell Stone's work is predominantly black and white self-portraits. She first took an analog photography class in high school<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.wmagazine.com/story/young-photographers-to-follow-2020/|title=These Are the 8 Young Photographers to Follow in 2020|website=W Magazine {{!}} Women's Fashion & Celebrity News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> and continues to use film in her practice, primarily shooting with a Pentax.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nStone was a featured photographer in W Magazine's \"These Are the 8 Young Photographers to Follow in 2020\".<ref name=\":0\" />  She attributes her interest in representation and self-portraiture to growing up with [[Myspace]].<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\nHer series \"Natura Negra\" explores the connection of black bodies and nature, specifically the nature that can be found in dense cities<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.kqed.org/arts/13873630/the-faces-and-conversations-of-moads-winter-2020-opening-reception|title=The Faces and Conversations of MoAD's Winter Opening Reception|website=KQED|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> or what she refers to as \"urban nature\".<ref name=\":0\" /> This series sets out to reclaim and reconnect black bodies to nature, even if it is in an urban setting.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.moadsf.org/exhibition/moad-emerging-artists-presents-chanell-stone/|title=MoAD Emerging Artists presents Chanell Stone|website=MoAD Museum of African Diaspora|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> \"Natura Negra\" won her an emerging artist award from the [[Museum of the African Diaspora]] in San Francisco.\n\n\n== Awards and fellowships ==\nAmong the honors which Stone has earned are:\n\n2020 Artist in Residence, Real Time and Space<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.realtimeandspace.org/residency-2/|title=REAL TIME & SPACE {{!}} RESIDENCY|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n2019-2020 Emerging Artist Award, [[Museum of the African Diaspora]] San Francisco<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moadsf.org/connect/emerging-artists-program/|title=Emerging Artists Program|website=MoAD Museum of African Diaspora|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n2018-2019\u00a0 Purchase Prize Award, [[Center for Photography at Woodstock]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cpw.org/news/about-photography-now-2018/|title=CPW \u2014 Photography Now 2018|website=www.cpw.org|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n2018-2019\u00a0 Kate V. and Harry W. Davies Memorial Scholarship, California College of the Arts\n\n2017-2019\u00a0 Diversity Scholarship, California College of the Arts\n\n2017-2019\u00a0 Faculty Honors Scholarship, California College of the Arts\n\n== Selected exhibitions ==\nStone\u2019s work has been featured in exhibitions at numerous galleries and institutions including:\n\n* [[Berkeley Art Center]], Berkeley, CA \u201cExperiments in the Field: Creative Collaboration in the Age of Ecological Concern\u201d (2020)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mutualart.com/Exhibition/Experiments-in-the-Field--Creative-Colla/D74EE38665E0BFEA|title=MutualArt.com - The Web's Largest Art Information Service.|website=www.mutualart.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n*[[Museum of the African Diaspora]], San Francisco, CA, \u201cNatura Negra\u201d (2020)<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n* [[Aperture Foundation]], New York, NY, \u201cAperture Summer Open: Delirious Cities\u201d (2019)\n\n* [[SF Camerawork]], San Francisco, CA, \u201cForecast\u201d (2019)\n\n* Hit Gallery, San Francisco, CA, \u201cBrass Tacks\u201d (2019)\n\n* Kala Art Institute, Berkeley, CA, \u201cPoetics of Conflict\u201d (2018)\n\n* [[Center for Photography at Woodstock]], Woodstock, NY, \u201cPhotography Now\u201d (2018)\n\n* Ortega y Gasset Projects, Brooklyn, NY, \u201cVice Versa\u201d (2018)\n\n== Collections ==\nStone's work is held in collections including:\n\n* [[Center for Photography at Woodstock]], Woodstock, NY\n\n* Meyer Library: Artist Book Collection, Oakland, CA\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Official site|https://www.chanellstone.com/}}\n", "text_old": "#REDIRECT [[Chanell Stone]]\n\n{{Redirect category shell|\n{{R from move}}\n}}\n", "name_user": "Ambear13", "label": "safe", "comment": "citations added #noweditingaf #artandfeminism #ccarts", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chanell_stone"}
{"title_page": "Gugan Singh Ranga", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=May 2018}}\n{{one source|date=February 2015}}\n'''Gugan Singh Ranga''' (born 7 September 1948) was a leader of [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] and a former member of the [[Delhi Legislative Assembly]] from Bawana.\n\nHe joined Aam aadmi party on 30 July 2017 in presence of Delhi chief minister Arvind kejriwal.<ref>http://myneta.info/delhi2013/candidate.php?candidate_id=178</ref> '''Gugan Singh Ranga''' was the contested from the [[North West Delhi (Lok Sabha constituency)|North West Delhi]] parliamentary constituency as a AAP party candidate for the 2019 Lok Sabha Elections he lost the contest by a margin of around [[2019 Indian general election in Delhi|5,53,897]] from [[Hans Raj Hans]].\n\nHe [https://www.firstpost.com/politics/gugan-singh-rejoins-bjp-ahead-of-delhi-assembly-polls-aaps-manish-sisodia-says-defection-is-poll-season-phenomenon-7842571.html returned] BJP on 30 December,2019 in the presence of Union minister Prakash Javadekar and Delhi BJP chief Manoj Tiwari. \n\n==Political Career==\n\n===2019 Lok Sabha Election===\n'''Gugan Singh Ranga''' was the contested from the [[North West Delhi (Lok Sabha constituency)|North West Delhi]] parliamentary constituency as a AAP party candidate for the 2019 Lok Sabha Elections he lost the contest by a margin of around [[2019 Indian general election in Delhi|5,53,897]] from [[Hans Raj Hans]].\n\n===2013 Delhi Assembly elections===\n\nGugan was elected from the reserved assembly constituency of Bawana on a BJP ticket in 2013, but was defeated by AAP\u2019s Ved Prakash in the 2015 polls. \n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ranga, Gugan Singh}}\n[[Category:Delhi MLAs 2013\u20132015]]\n[[Category:1948 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Bharatiya Janata Party politicians from Delhi]]\n\n\n{{BJP-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=May 2018}}\n{{one source|date=February 2015}}\n'''Gugan Singh Ranga''' (born 1948) was a leader of [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] and a former member of the [[Delhi Legislative Assembly]].\n\nNow he has joined Aam aadmi party on 30 July 2017 in presence of Delhi chief minister Arvind kejriwal.<ref>http://myneta.info/delhi2013/candidate.php?candidate_id=178</ref>\n\n==Political Career==\n\n===2019 Lok Sabha Election===\n'''Gugan Singh Ranga''' will be contesting from the [[North West Delhi (Lok Sabha constituency)|North West Delhi]] parliamentary constituency as a AAP party candidate for the 2019 Lok Sabha Elections.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ranga, Gugan Singh}}\n[[Category:Delhi MLAs 2013\u20132015]]\n[[Category:1948 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Bharatiya Janata Party politicians from Delhi]]\n\n\n{{BJP-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "AakashSharmaHub", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added more details about Gugan Singh", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gugan_Singh_Ranga"}
{"title_page": "Back to Me (Lindsay Lohan song)", "text_new": "{{under construction}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name = Back to Me\n| cover = Lindsay_Lohan_-_Back_to_Me.png\n| alt =\n| type = single\n| artist = [[Lindsay Lohan]]\n| album =\n| released = April 3, 2020\n| format = {{hlist|[[Music download|Digital download]]|[[music streaming|streaming]]}}\n| recorded =\n| studio =\n| genre = [[Electropop]]<ref>{{cite web |last1=Nolfi |first1=Joey |title=Lindsay Lohan drops new pop banger 'Back to Me,' her first song in 12 years |url=https://ew.com/music/lindsay-lohan-new-song-back-to-me/ |website=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |accessdate=April 3, 2020 |date=April 3, 2020}}</ref>\n| length = 2:53\n| label = {{hlist|[[Republic Records|Republic]]|[[Casablanca Records| Casablanca]]}}\n| writer = {{hlist|[[Alma (Finnish singer)|Alma]]|Chiara Hunter|[[Mark Ralph (record producer)|Mark Ralph]]}}\n| producer = Mark Ralph\n| prev_title = [[Bossy (Lindsay Lohan song)|Bossy]]\n| prev_year  = 2008\n}}\n\n\"'''Back to Me'''\" is a song recorded by American actress and singer [[Lindsay Lohan]]. The song was released on April 3, 2020, by [[Republic Records]]. It is Lohan\u2019s first single in twelve years. It was written by [[Alma (Finnish singer)|Alma]], Chiara Hunter and [[Mark Ralph (record producer)|Mark Ralph]], who also produced the song.\n\n==Background==\nIn June 2019, it was announced that Lohan signed a new recording contract with [[Casablanca Records]]. She was previously signed to the label, which released her albums ''[[Speak (Lindsay Lohan album)|Speak]]'' and ''[[A Little More Personal (Raw)]]'' in 2004 and 2005, respectively. It was also revealed that the singer was working on new music with \"a small team of producers and songwriters\", having already completed a few songs for an upcoming project.<ref>https://www.usmagazine.com/entertainment/news/lindsay-lohan-signs-record-deal-already-finished-a-few-songs</ref> On August 29, Lohan premiered a snippet of \"Xanax\", her first new song since 2008's \"[[Bossy (Lindsay Lohan song)|Bossy]]\", on [[Kris Fade]]'s [[Virgin Radio|Virgin Radio Dubai]] show.<ref>https://variety.com/2019/music/news/lindsay-lohan-new-song-xanax-1203318839</ref> While it has yet to be officially released, the singer posted the entire song on her [[Instagram]] account, alongside what [[Vulture.com]] described as a \"homemade music video\"<ref>https://www.vulture.com/2019/09/lindsay-lohan-xanax-new-song-instagram.html</ref> that was later deleted. After teasing the release of new music for several more months, Lohan announced in January 2020 that she would be releasing her long-awaited third studio album at the end of February.<ref>https://www.yahoo.com/entertainment/lindsay-lohan-reveals-her-album-185857132.html</ref>\n\nOn March 31, the singer released a \"cryptic video\" that officially announced her musical comeback. The video, which she posted on all of her social media accounts, \"opens on a dark room filled with several television sets, all of which display images from throughout Lohan's career, including paparazzi shots and scenes from her \"[[Rumors (Lindsay Lohan song)|Rumors]]\" music video \u2014 all while a distorted song softly plays in the background\". The next day, she revealed that she would be releasing \"Back to Me\", her first new single in 12 years, on April 3. Lohan also shared a short snippet of the song and explained that it is about \"rediscovering and accepting oneself, shutting out the noise and moving forward and letting the past go. Living in the now\".<ref>https://ew.com/music/lindsay-lohan-new-song</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\nUpon release, \"Back to Me\" received positive reviews from critics, most of whom complimented Lohan's return to music. ''[[Billboard charts|Billboard]]'' called the song \"chill track with an upbeat club vibe\" and highlighted its lyrics for Lohan confronting her difficult years growing up in the public eye, and how she\u2019s become stronger from the experience.<ref>https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/9350164/lindsay-lohan-back-to-me-listen</ref> ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' called the song \"a breezy, infectiously catchy electro-pop gem\" and also noted that the song sees her singing about \"reconnecting with herself in the wake of past trauma\".<ref>https://ew.com/music/lindsay-lohan-new-song-back-to-me/</ref> The ''[[Daily Mail]]'' also noted the song as a return to form for Lohan and complimented her \"smoky vocals\" from the opening seconds of the song.\n\n==Track listing==\n*'''Digital download and streaming'''<ref name=\"Apple Music\">{{cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/nz/album/back-to-me-single/1502651175|title=Back To Me \u2013 Single by Lindsay Lohan|website=[[Apple Music]]|accessdate=April 3, 2020}}</ref>\n#\"Back to Me\" \u2014 2:53\n\n==Release history==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! Country\n! Date\n! Format\n! Label\n! {{abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Various\n| April 3, 2020\n| {{hlist|[[Music download|Digital download]]|[[Streaming media|streaming]]}}\n| [[Republic Records]]\n|<ref name=\"Apple Music\">{{cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/nz/album/back-to-me-single/1502651175|title=Back To Me \u2013 Single by Lindsay Lohan|website=[[Apple Music]]|accessdate=April 3, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{MetroLyrics song|lindsay-lohan|back-to-me}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n*{{YouTube|esuHhGVxi3g|Back to Me (Audio)}}\n\n{{Lindsay Lohan}}\n\n[[Category:2020 songs]]\n[[Category:2020 singles]]\n[[Category:Republic Records singles]]\n[[Category:Lindsay Lohan songs]]\n[[Category:Songs produced by Mark Ralph]]\n", "text_old": "{{under construction}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name = Back to Me\n| cover = Lindsay_Lohan_-_Back_to_Me.png\n| alt =\n| type = single\n| artist = [[Lindsay Lohan]]\n| album =\n| released = April 3, 2020\n| format = {{hlist|[[Music download|Digital download]]|[[music streaming|streaming]]}}\n| recorded =\n| studio =\n| genre = [[Electropop]]<ref>{{cite web |last1=Nolfi |first1=Joey |title=Lindsay Lohan drops new pop banger 'Back to Me,' her first song in 12 years |url=https://ew.com/music/lindsay-lohan-new-song-back-to-me/ |website=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |accessdate=April 3, 2020 |date=April 3, 2020}}</ref>\n| length = 2:53\n| label = {{hlist|[[Republic Records|Republic]]|[[Casablanca Records| Casablanca]]}}\n| writer = {{hlist|[[Alma (Finnish singer)|Alma]]|Chiara Hunter|[[Mark Ralph (record producer)|Mark Ralph]]}}\n| producer = Mark Ralph\n| prev_title = [[Bossy (Lindsay Lohan song)|Bossy]]\n| prev_year  = 2008\n}}\n\n\"'''Back to Me'''\" is a song recorded by American actress and singer [[Lindsay Lohan]]. The song was released on April 3, 2020, by [[Republic Records]]. It is Lohan\u2019s first single in twelve years. It was written by [[Alma (Finnish singer)|Alma]], Chiara Hunter and [[Mark Ralph (record producer)|Mark Ralph]], who also produced the song.\n\n==Background==\nIn June 2019, it was announced that Lohan signed a new recording contract with [[Casablanca Records]]. She was previously signed to the label, which released her albums ''[[Speak (Lindsay Lohan album)|Speak]]'' and ''[[A Little More Personal (Raw)]]'' in 2004 and 2005, respectively. It was also revealed that the singer was working on new music with \"a small team of producers and songwriters\", having already completed a few songs for an upcoming project.<ref>https://www.usmagazine.com/entertainment/news/lindsay-lohan-signs-record-deal-already-finished-a-few-songs</ref> On August 29, Lohan premiered a snippet of \"Xanax\", her first new song since 2008's \"[[Bossy (Lindsay Lohan song)|Bossy]]\", on [[Kris Fade]]'s [[Virgin Radio|Virgin Radio Dubai]] show.<ref>https://variety.com/2019/music/news/lindsay-lohan-new-song-xanax-1203318839</ref> While it has yet to be officially released, the singer posted the entire song on her [[Instagram]] account, alongside what [[Vulture.com]] described as a \"homemade music video\"<ref>https://www.vulture.com/2019/09/lindsay-lohan-xanax-new-song-instagram.html</ref> that was later deleted. After teasing the release of new music for several more months, Lohan announced in January 2020 that she would be releasing her long-awaited third studio album at the end of February.<ref>https://www.yahoo.com/entertainment/lindsay-lohan-reveals-her-album-185857132.html</ref>\n\nOn March 31, the singer released a \"cryptic video\" that officially announced her musical comeback. The video, which she posted on all of her social media accounts, \"opens on a dark room filled with several television sets, all of which display images from throughout Lohan's career, including paparazzi shots and scenes from her \"[[Rumors (Lindsay Lohan song)|Rumors]]\" music video \u2014 all while a distorted song softly plays in the background\". The next day, she revealed that she would be releasing \"Back to Me\", her first new single in 12 years, on April 3. Lohan also shared a short snippet of the song and explained that it is about \"rediscovering and accepting oneself, shutting out the noise and moving forward and letting the past go. Living in the now\".<ref>https://ew.com/music/lindsay-lohan-new-song</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n\nUpon release, \"Back to Me\" received positive reviews from critics, most of whom complimented Lohan's return to music. [[Billboard charts|Billboard]] called the song \"chill track with an upbeat club vibe\" and highlighted its lyrics for Lohan confronting her difficult years growing up in the public eye, and how she\u2019s become stronger from the experience.<ref>https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/9350164/lindsay-lohan-back-to-me-listen</ref> [[Entertainment Weekly]] called the song \"a breezy, infectiously catchy electro-pop gem\" and also noted that the song sees her singing about \"reconnecting with herself in the wake of past trauma\".<ref>https://ew.com/music/lindsay-lohan-new-song-back-to-me/</ref> The [[Daily Mail]] also noted the song as a return to form for Lohan and complimented her \"smoky vocals\" from the opening seconds of the song.\n\n==Track listing==\n*'''Digital download and streaming'''<ref name=\"Apple Music\">{{cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/nz/album/back-to-me-single/1502651175|title=Back To Me \u2013 Single by Lindsay Lohan|website=[[Apple Music]]|accessdate=April 3, 2020}}</ref>\n#\"Back to Me\" \u2014 2:53\n\n==Release history==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! Country\n! Date\n! Format\n! Label\n! {{abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Various\n| April 3, 2020\n| {{hlist|[[Music download|Digital download]]|[[Streaming media|streaming]]}}\n| [[Republic Records]]\n|<ref name=\"Apple Music\">{{cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/nz/album/back-to-me-single/1502651175|title=Back To Me \u2013 Single by Lindsay Lohan|website=[[Apple Music]]|accessdate=April 3, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{MetroLyrics song|lindsay-lohan|back-to-me}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n*{{YouTube|esuHhGVxi3g|Back to Me (Audio)}}\n\n{{Lindsay Lohan}}\n\n[[Category:2020 songs]]\n[[Category:2020 singles]]\n[[Category:Republic Records singles]]\n[[Category:Lindsay Lohan songs]]\n[[Category:Songs produced by Mark Ralph]]\n", "name_user": "Kbabej", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCritical reception:magazines are italicized", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Back_to_Me_(Lindsay_Lohan_song)"}
